## Objectives of Teaching — Complete Coverage---

### What Are the Objectives of Teaching?

The objectives of teaching answer one simple question: **What should happen inside the learner as a result of teaching?** The answer falls into three big categories — called the three domains of educational objectives — given by Benjamin Bloom and his colleagues in 1956. This is called **Bloom's Taxonomy** and it is one of the most heavily tested topics in UGC NET Paper 1.

---

### Domain 1 — Cognitive Domain (Head)

This deals with intellectual development — knowledge, understanding, and thinking ability.

Bloom gave six levels in ascending order of complexity: Remember (recall facts — lowest), Understand (explain in own words), Apply (use knowledge in new situations), Analyse (break down into parts), Evaluate (make judgements), and Create (produce something new — highest). The revised taxonomy by Anderson & Krathwohl (2001) changed "Synthesis" to "Create" and reordered slightly — UGC NET now follows the revised version.

Exam tip: If asked "which is the highest level of Bloom's cognitive domain?" — answer is Create (or Synthesis in the original version). If asked "lowest level" — answer is Remember (or Knowledge).

---

### Domain 2 — Affective Domain (Heart)

This deals with emotions, attitudes, values, and feelings — the inner world of the learner.

Krathwohl gave five levels: Receiving (being willing to pay attention), Responding (actively participating), Valuing (assigning worth to something), Organising (building a value system), and Characterising (living by that value system consistently — highest level).

Example: A student initially ignores environmental issues (receiving), then starts reading about them (responding), then believes pollution is wrong (valuing), then prioritises eco-friendly choices (organising), then lives as an environmental activist (characterising).

---

### Domain 3 — Psychomotor Domain (Hand)

This deals with physical skills, coordination, and motor abilities.

Simpson gave the most commonly cited classification: Perception, Set (mental readiness), Guided response (learning by imitation), Mechanism (habit formation), Complex overt response (skilled performance), Adaptation, and Origination (creating new movements — highest).

Example: Learning to write, perform a surgical procedure, play a musical instrument, or use laboratory equipment.

---

### Specific Objectives of Teaching (Direct Answer)

Beyond the three domains, UGC NET expects you to know the specific objectives:

To impart knowledge (cognitive), to develop understanding of concepts and principles, to develop the ability to apply knowledge, to cultivate positive attitudes and values (affective), to develop practical and vocational skills (psychomotor), to develop critical and creative thinking, to prepare citizens for democratic society, and to promote self-learning and lifelong learning.

---

### Immediate vs. Final Objectives

Another distinction UGC NET tests: Immediate objectives are lesson-level goals (by the end of today's class, the student will be able to...). Final objectives are broad, long-term aims of education (develop the whole personality of the learner).

---

### Memory Formula for the Exam

> 3 Domains = CAP → Cognitive (Bloom, 6 levels) · Affective (Krathwohl, 5 levels) · Psychomotor (Simpson, 7 levels)
> Easy recall: **Head · Heart · Hand**

